  "eprint": {
    "title": "New Complexity Trade-Offs for the (Multiple) Number Field Sieve Algorithm in Non-Prime Fields",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Palash Sarkar",
        "email": "singh@gmail",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Shashank Singh",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "The selection of polynomials to represent number fields crucially determines the efficiency of the Number Field Sieve\n(NFS) algorithm for solving the discrete logarithm in a finite field. An important recent work due to Barbulescu et al. builds upon\nexisting works to propose two new methods for polynomial selection when the target field is a non-prime field. These methods are\ncalled the generalised Joux-Lercier (GJL) and the Conjugation methods. In this work, we propose a new method (which we denote\nas $\\mathcal{A}$) for polynomial selection for the NFS algorithm in fields $\\mathbb{F}_{Q}$, with $Q=p^n$ and $n>1$.\nThe new method both subsumes and generalises the GJL and the Conjugation methods and provides new trade-offs for both $n$ composite\nand $n$ prime. Let us denote the variant of the (multiple) NFS algorithm using the polynomial selection method ``{X}\" by (M)NFS-{X}.\nAsymptotic analysis is performed for both the NFS-$\\mathcal{A}$ and the MNFS-$\\mathcal{A}$ algorithms.\nIn particular, when $p=L_Q(2/3,c_p)$, for $c_p\\in [3.39,20.91]$, the complexity of NFS-$\\mathcal{A}$ is better than the complexities\nof all previous algorithms whether classical or MNFS. The MNFS-$\\mathcal{A}$ algorithm provides lower complexity compared to\nNFS-$\\mathcal{A}$ algorithm; for $c_p\\in (0, 1.12] \\cup [1.45,3.15]$, the complexity of MNFS-$\\mathcal{A}$\nis the same as that of the MNFS-Conjugation and for $c_p\\notin (0, 1.12] \\cup [1.45,3.15]$, the complexity of MNFS-$\\mathcal{A}$\nis lower than that of all previous methods.",
